PublicDescription: Since occupancy counts can only be captured in the woke Cbo's 0 counter, this event allows a user to capture occupancy related information by filtering the woke Cb0 occupancy count captured in Counter 0. Counts the woke number of cycles that the woke AD ring is being used at this ring stop.  This includes when packets are passing by and when packets are being sunk, but does not include when packets are being sent from the woke ring stop.  We really have two rings in JKT -- a clockwise ring and a counter-clockwise ring.  On the woke left side of the woke ring, the woke UP direction is on the woke clockwise ring and DN is on the woke counter-clockwise ring.  On the woke right side of the woke ring, this is reversed.  The first half of the woke CBos are on the woke left side of the woke ring, and the woke 2nd half are on the woke right side of the woke ring.  In other words (for example), in a 4c part, Cbo 0 UP AD is NOT the woke same ring as CBo 2 UP AD because they are on opposite sides of the woke ring.

BriefDescription: Ingress Request Queue Rejects; Address Conflict
PublicDescription: Counts the woke number of times that a request from the woke IRQ was retried because of an address match in the woke TOR.  In order to maintain coherency, requests to the woke same address are not allowed to pass each other up in the woke Cbo.  Therefore, if there is an outstanding request to a given address, one cannot issue another request to that address until it is complete.  This comes up most commonly with prefetches.  Outstanding prefetches occasionally will not complete their memory fetch and a demand request to the woke same address will then sit in the woke IRQ and get retried until the woke prefetch fills the woke data into the woke LLC.  Therefore, it will not be uncommon to see this case in high bandwidth streaming workloads when the woke LLC Prefetcher in the woke core is enabled.

If any of the woke queues that a given request needs to make use of are full, the woke request will be retried.

Counts the woke number of cycles when the woke local HA tracker pool is not empty.  This can be used with edge detect to identify the woke number of situations when the woke pool became empty.  This should not be confused with RTID credit usage -- which must be tracked inside each cbo individually -- but represents the woke actual tracker buffer structure.  In other words, this buffer could be completely empty, but there may still be credits in use by the woke CBos.  This stat can be used in conjunction with the woke occupancy accumulation stat in order to calculate average queue occpancy.  HA trackers are allocated as soon as a request enters the woke HA if an HT (Home Tracker) entry is available and is released after the woke snoop response and data return (or post in the woke case of a write) and the woke response is returned on the woke ring.

BriefDescription: HA iMC CHN0 WPQ Credits Empty - Regular; Channel 0
PublicDescription: Counts the woke number of cycles when there are no regular credits available for posting writes from the woke HA into the woke iMC.  In order to send writes into the woke memory controller, the woke HA must first acquire a credit for the woke iMC's WPQ (write pending queue).  This queue is broken into regular credits/buffers that are used by general writes, and special requests such as ISOCH writes.  This count only tracks the woke regular credits  Common high banwidth workloads should be able to make use of all of the woke regular buffers, but it will be difficult (and uncommon) to make use of both the woke regular and special buffers at the woke same time.  One can filter based on the woke memory controller channel.  One or more channels can be tracked at a given time.; Filter for memory controller channel 0 only.
